00:05:02.828 --> 00:05:06.188
<v Guest> So, you know, if you're, if you're trying to figure out who has the most potential

00:05:06.188 --> 00:05:09.698
<v Guest> in a classroom, you look at who has the best grades. If you're trying to figure out

00:05:09.698 --> 00:05:12.928
<v Guest> who has the most potential in a sport, you look at who's already the star player.

00:05:12.928 --> 00:05:16.818
<v Guest> And what we miss when we do that is we don't see how much

00:05:16.818 --> 00:05:19.918
<v Guest> scaffolding somebody had to get to that point.

00:05:19.918 --> 00:05:23.438
<v Guest> We don't see how many advantages they had, how many disadvantages

00:05:23.438 --> 00:05:24.778
<v Guest> they might have overcome.

00:05:24.778 --> 00:05:28.438
<v Guest> And I think a much better way to gauge potential is to look at

00:05:28.438 --> 00:05:30.048
<v Guest> how much progress somebody has made.

