<v Guest> The other one starts out with a C- and works their way up to an A-.

00:05:38.868 --> 00:05:42.068
<v Guest> I think the second student has shown a lot more potential.

00:05:42.068 --> 00:05:45.598
<v Guest> They've demonstrated a capacity to learn and grow. And that's what

00:05:45.598 --> 00:05:47.388
<v Guest> I think potential is all about.

00:05:47.388 --> 00:05:51.198
<v Mel> I love that. And I think it's so important for everybody listening

00:05:51.198 --> 00:05:54.918
<v Mel> to really let that sink in because it's not about where you start.

00:05:54.918 --> 00:05:58.468
<v Mel> It's about the progress that you make. And I think that's so empowering

00:05:58.468 --> 00:06:01.888
<v Mel> because it means that anybody, regardless of their circumstances,

00:06:01.888 --> 00:06:04.208
<v Mel> can achieve their potential.

00:06:04.208 --> 00:06:07.818
<v Guest> Yeah, I think that's right. And I think that, you know, one of the things that

00:06:07.818 --> 00:06:11.438
<v Guest> I try to do in the book is to show that there are these skills

00:06:11.438 --> 00:06:14.888
<v Guest> of character that we can all develop that allow us to punch

00:06:14.888 --> 00:06:16.328
<v Guest> above our weight.

00:06:16.328 --> 00:06:19.928
<v Guest> And these are things like being proactive, being a sponge,

00:06:19.928 --> 00:06:23.568
<v Guest> being an imperfectionist, being a structure builder.

00:06:23.568 --> 00:06:27.028
<v Guest> And these are not fixed traits. They're learnable skills.

00:06:27.028 --> 00:06:30.598
<v Guest> And I think that's one of the most exciting things about the science of potential.

00:06:30.598 --> 00:06:33.998
<v Mel> So let's talk about those skills because I think that's really where the rubber

00:06:33.998 --> 00:06:35.138
<v Mel> meets the road.

00:06:35.138 --> 00:06:38.648
<v Mel> You talk about these three character skills.

00:06:38.648 --> 00:06:42.278
<v Mel> The first one is being proactive. What does that mean?

00:06:42.278 --> 00:06:45.898
<v Guest> So being proactive is about taking initiative. It's about

00:06:45.898 --> 00:06:49.498
<v Guest> not waiting for permission or for instructions. It's about

00:06:49.498 --> 00:06:52.848
<v Guest> seeing a problem and trying to solve it, or seeing an opportunity

00:06:52.848 --> 00:06:54.278
<v Guest> and trying to seize it.

00:06:54.278 --> 00:06:57.988
<v Guest> And I think that, you know, a lot of people think that proactivity is something

00:06:57.988 --> 00:07:00.028
<v Guest> that you're either born with or you're not.

00:07:00.028 --> 00:07:03.448
<v Guest> But the evidence actually shows that it's a skill that you can learn.

00:07:03.448 --> 00:07:07.038
<v Guest> And one of the ways you can learn it is by practicing what I call

00:07:07.038 --> 00:07:08.838
<v Guest> "job crafting."

00:07:08.838 --> 00:07:12.378
<v Mel> Okay, so what is job crafting? Because that sounds really interesting.

00:07:12.378 --> 00:07:16.038
<v Guest> So job crafting is basically redesigning your job to make it

00:07:16.038 --> 00:07:17.508
<v Guest> more meaningful and engaging.

00:07:17.508 --> 00:07:21.038
<v Guest> And there are three ways to do it. The first is task crafting,

00:07:21.038 --> 00:07:24.378
<v Guest> which is changing the number or the scope or the nature of your tasks.

00:07:24.378 --> 00:07:28.108
<v Guest> The second is relational crafting, which is changing who you interact with

00:07:28.108 --> 00:07:29.188
<v Guest> on the job.

00:07:29.188 --> 00:07:32.618
<v Guest> And the third is cognitive crafting, which is changing how you think

00:07:32.618 --> 00:07:34.038
<v Guest> about your job.

00:07:34.038 --> 00:07:37.668
<v Mel> Okay, so give me an example of how somebody could use job crafting

00:07:37.668 --> 00:07:39.708
<v Mel> to be more proactive.

00:07:39.708 --> 00:07:43.208
<v Guest> So let's say you're a hospital cleaner, and your job is to clean rooms.

00:07:43.208 --> 00:07:46.858
<v Guest> That's the task. But you could task craft by saying,

00:07:46.858 --> 00:07:50.458
<v Guest> "You know what? I'm not just going to clean rooms. I'm going to try to make

00:07:50.458 --> 00:07:52.698
<v Guest> patients feel more comfortable."

00:07:52.698 --> 00:07:56.098
<v Guest> So you might rearrange the flowers, or you might, you know,

00:07:56.098 --> 00:07:58.908
<v Guest> talk to the patients and try to cheer them up.

00:07:58.908 --> 00:08:02.488
<v Guest> That's task crafting. Relational crafting would be, you know,

00:08:02.488 --> 00:08:05.908
<v Guest> instead of just interacting with the nurses, you might also interact

00:08:05.908 --> 00:08:08.008
<v Guest> with the doctors or the patients' families.

00:08:08.008 --> 00:08:11.638
<v Guest> And cognitive crafting would be to say, "You know what? My job is not just

00:08:11.638 --> 00:08:14.998
<v Guest> to clean rooms. My job is to help heal people."

00:08:14.998 --> 00:08:18.498
<v Guest> And when you do those things, you're taking initiative, you're being proactive,

00:08:18.498 --> 00:08:21.698
<v Guest> and you're making your job more meaningful and engaging.

00:08:21.698 --> 00:08:25.208
<v Mel> I love that. And I think that's such a powerful example because it shows

00:08:25.208 --> 00:08:28.788
<v Mel> that even if you're in a job that you don't necessarily love,

00:08:28.788 --> 00:08:32.208
<v Mel> you can still find ways to make it more meaningful and engaging.

00:08:32.208 --> 00:08:35.848
<v Guest> Exactly. And I think that, you know, the research on job crafting shows

00:08:35.848 --> 00:08:39.498
<v Guest> that it leads to higher job satisfaction, higher performance,

00:08:39.498 --> 00:08:41.368
<v Guest> and lower burnout.

00:08:41.368 --> 00:08:44.768
<v Guest> So it's a really powerful tool for unlocking your potential.

00:08:44.768 --> 00:08:48.298
<v Mel> Okay, so the second character skill you talk about is being a sponge.

00:08:48.298 --> 00:08:50.008
<v Mel> What does that mean?

00:08:50.008 --> 00:08:53.478
<v Guest> So being a sponge is about being open to learning and feedback.

00:08:53.478 --> 00:08:57.078
<v Guest> It's about recognizing that you don't know everything and that you can

00:08:57.078 --> 00:08:58.738
<v Guest> always learn from others.

00:08:58.738 --> 00:09:02.268
<v Guest> And I think that, you know, a lot of people are afraid of feedback

00:09:02.268 --> 00:09:05.348
<v Guest> because they see it as criticism. But if you can reframe it

00:09:05.348 --> 00:09:08.308
<v Guest> as an opportunity to learn and grow, then it becomes

00:09:08.308 --> 00:09:09.798
<v Guest> a really valuable tool.

00:09:09.798 --> 00:09:13.288
<v Mel> And how do you become more of a sponge? Because I think a lot of people

00:09:13.288 --> 00:09:16.638
<v Mel> do struggle with receiving feedback, especially if it's negative.

00:09:16.638 --> 00:09:20.088
<v Guest> So one way is to actively seek out feedback.

00:09:20.088 --> 00:09:23.478
<v Guest> Don't wait for it to come to you. Go ask for it.

00:09:23.478 --> 00:09:26.868
<v Guest> And when you get it, try to listen with an open mind.

